data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | **Constructor** |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | **Class fixture** via `IClassFixture<T>` |

Here's the converted class:

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)  // injects fixture
    {
        // Per-test setup (SetUp)
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Per-test teardown (TearDown)
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- xUnit creates a **new instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` run for each test automatically.
- `IClassFixture<T>` ensures `DatabaseFixture` is created once and shared across all tests in the class.
- Assertions change: `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`, and note `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` — expected comes **first**.
